fix #1930 unwrap .Terms(new List<T>) to just T

When calling

```csharp
.Terms(new List<T>());
```

The user expects T[] to be written to elasticsearch but due to C#
resolution they end up calling

```csharp
.Terms<List<T>>(params List<T>)
```

to T[] when a single IEnumerable is passed as T, special casing `string`
to be exluded from the unwrapping behavior so we do not unwrap string to
char[]

Reoganise into Stages

Ensure that each stage of the compiler is grouped in the `.fsproj`. This
should also help ensure that each stage of the compilation pipeline
only dpends on those before it.

Functional Lexer Interface

Make the lexer type itself internal. Introduce a new functional
interface to the lexer. We still need the lexer interface _for now_ to
provide the parser with rich position information. Ideally the lexer
could be _only_ accessed via the functional interface. This would need
a bigger restructuring of parsing however.

Functional Lexer

Convert the lexer over to a purely functional interface. Lexer objects
are no more. The lexer is simply a function that takes a sequence of
characters and returns the corresponding sequence of lexical tokens.

Lexing of Perculiar Numbers

Odd number prefixes that could be confused by the lexer for identifiers.

Reformat Things

Simplify the API Layout of the Lex module. No need for a nested module
to store the token sets any longer.

Functional Parser

Move the parser from an object to a collection of functions. Each parser
function takes a `state` as the final parameter, and returns a new state
to allow for modifications.

This is the same approach taken with `Firethorn` recently in the
Predciated` project.

Handle `expect` at EOF

issue.title: Checking for Whole Text Matches
issue.body:
An issue rust-onig/rust-onig#171 has been raised on the `onig` crate to do with the behaviour of our `is_match` function. I don't
know if there's a better way to do what we're trying to do here or if there's a bug in Oniguruma's longest
matching support.

The `is_match` function is used to check if the whole input text matches the given pattern. It's implemented
by calling `onig_match_with_param` passing in `SEARCH_OPTION_NONE` and no region or match param.

This works fine when the pattern can only match in one way. When there are alternations in the pattern
however we can end up with problems due to the order of the alternations. e.g. given the pattern `a|abc`
and the search text `abc` the `is_match` check fails. Oniguruma finds the first match of the pattern in
the text which is just the initial `a`.

I've tried using the `(?L)` flag, along with `ONIG_OPTION_FIND_LONGEST` but can't seem to work out
a combination of parameters that will make the pattern match the full text. Switching the order of the
pattern to `abc|a` makes the match work. It seems that Oniguruma is performing a depth-first match and
returning as soon as some match is found. is there a way of getting the longer match here?

comment.body: A search time option to force a match to the end of the string sounds like exactly what we want here. I’d be happy to try and implement it and open a PR.

review.body:
This changes the public API of the `match_with_param` and `search_with_param` functions to allow sharing a match param between more than one call. This seems like the better API, and
if we're bumping to 2021 we might as well. I don't imagine it will be too much of an issue as those
aren't the most widely used parts of the API.

issue.title: Checking for Whole Text Matches
issue.body:
An issue rust-onig/rust-onig#171 has been raised on the `onig` crate to do with the behaviour of our `is_match` function. I don't
know if there's a better way to do what we're trying to do here or if there's a bug in Oniguruma's longest
matching support.

The `is_match` function is used to check if the whole input text matches the given pattern. It's implemented
by calling `onig_match_with_param` passing in `SEARCH_OPTION_NONE` and no region or match param.

This works fine when the pattern can only match in one way. When there are alternations in the pattern
however we can end up with problems due to the order of the alternations. e.g. given the pattern `a|abc`
and the search text `abc` the `is_match` check fails. Oniguruma finds the first match of the pattern in
the text which is just the initial `a`.

I've tried using the `(?L)` flag, along with `ONIG_OPTION_FIND_LONGEST` but can't seem to work out
a combination of parameters that will make the pattern match the full text. Switching the order of the
pattern to `abc|a` makes the match work. It seems that Oniguruma is performing a depth-first match and
returning as soon as some match is found. is there a way of getting the longer match here?

comment.body: A search time option to force a match to the end of the string sounds like exactly what we want here. I’d be happy to try and implement it and open a PR.

review.body:
This changes the public API of the `match_with_param` and `search_with_param` functions to allow sharing a match param between more than one call. This seems like the better API, and
if we're bumping to 2021 we might as well. I don't imagine it will be too much of an issue as those
aren't the most widely used parts of the API.

issue.title: Checking for Whole Text Matches
issue.body:
An issue rust-onig/rust-onig#171 has been raised on the `onig` crate to do with the behaviour of our `is_match` function. I don't
know if there's a better way to do what we're trying to do here or if there's a bug in Oniguruma's longest
matching support.

The `is_match` function is used to check if the whole input text matches the given pattern. It's implemented
by calling `onig_match_with_param` passing in `SEARCH_OPTION_NONE` and no region or match param.

This works fine when the pattern can only match in one way. When there are alternations in the pattern
however we can end up with problems due to the order of the alternations. e.g. given the pattern `a|abc`
and the search text `abc` the `is_match` check fails. Oniguruma finds the first match of the pattern in
the text which is just the initial `a`.

I've tried using the `(?L)` flag, along with `ONIG_OPTION_FIND_LONGEST` but can't seem to work out
a combination of parameters that will make the pattern match the full text. Switching the order of the
pattern to `abc|a` makes the match work. It seems that Oniguruma is performing a depth-first match and
returning as soon as some match is found. is there a way of getting the longer match here?

comment.body: A search time option to force a match to the end of the string sounds like exactly what we want here. I’d be happy to try and implement it and open a PR.
